From cou.: 58 Fig. 5 shows the corresponding potential (a) and concentration (b) profiles at the top of the voltammetric wave. This corresponds to reversible electrode kinetics. Consequently, the Nernst equation is obeyed over the electrode surface and the flux is uniform. Again, the loss in the potential driving force is negligible (θ = −0.288 corresponds to E ≈ −7.39 × 10−3 V at 298 K), as expected for voltammetry at a steady-state.
